Date: Wed, 20 Sep 2000 10:24:51 -0500
From: H. Larry Penning <bevpenn@fgi.net>
Source: The Jerusalem Post News: Wed 20 Sep 2000 [edited

West Nile Fever Recognized as Epidemic
---------------------------------------
Three months after this year's first West Nile virus patient was diagnosed,
the Health Ministry yesterday held its first press conference on the subject
and admitted that what it has been calling an outbreak could be termed an
"epidemic." Ministry associate director-general Dr. Boaz Lev - who for weeks
had been saying there was "nothing unusual" and that the increased number of
cases was due to improved reporting due to new lab equipment at Sheba
Hospital at Tel Hashomer - now concedes there is an unusually large number
of cases. So far, 13 Israelis aged 54 to 90, mostly north of Tel Aviv, have
died, while an additional 161 have been infected. The virus is transmitted
solely by mosquitoes that have bitten infected animals, mostly poultry and
birds. Lev said that the autumn stay-over for a few weeks of migrating birds
in Israel and the hot, humid weather seemed to have increased the numbers of
cases. Healthy people need not worry, but the elderly and others of all ages
with weak immune systems and chronic illnesses should be careful by using
mosquito repellents and keeping indoors in the evening, when female
mosquitoes tend to bite. Lev also urged high-risk groups to go to their
health fund clinics for influenza and pneumococcal pneumonia vaccinations as
soon as possible.
[Byline: Judy Siegel-Itzkovich
--
H. Larry Penning
<bevpenn@fgi.net>
