Date: Thu, 21 Sep 2000 14:11:53 +0200
From: Manfred Green <m.green@trendline.co.il>

West Nile Virus in Israel
--------------------------
It is being reported on ProMED-mail that the Israel Ministry of Health had
officially declared an epidemic of West Nile Fever in Israel. The current
outbreak in Israel actually began in August, and questions have been raised
as to why has the term epidemic only been used now. Professionals in the
field will probably agree that technically there is no difference between
the terms epidemic and outbreak, and that the terms can be used
interchangeably to describe any unusual increase in cases of either
infectious or non-infectious diseases. The public [and politicians appears
to have a different perception of the terms "epidemic" and "outbreak", and
may view an "epidemic" as describing only the widespread occurrence of a
contagious disease (whose spread cannot be controlled?).Since the
communication of health risks to the public is an important issue, perhaps
we need to redefine the terminology and clarify our messages to the public.
For example, was the outbreak of West Nile Fever in New York in 1999, an
"epidemic"? If so, at what stage was it correct to call it an epidemic?
After the diagnosis of the first 2 cases? I'd be interested to hear
comments on this issue.
--
Manfred S. Green MD,PhD
Director,
Israel Center for Disease Control,
Ministry of Health,
Israel.
<m.green@trendline.co.il>
[To address Dr. Green's questions a search of existing documents on the
West Nile virus activity in the U.S. came up with the conclusion that the
WNV activity in 1999 was considered to be outbreak/epidemic. In a Mar 2000
document from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
(Epidemic/Epizootic West Nile Virus in the United States: Guidelines for
Surveillance, Prevention and Control, From a workshop cosponsored by the
Department of Health and Human Services, CDC and the U.S. Department of
Agriculture, Held in Fort Collins, Colorado, 8-9 Nov 1999), the background
section opens with "The epidemic of West Nile (WN) viral encephalitis in
the New York Metropolitan area in the summer of 1999 was unexpected and
underscores once again the ease with which human and animal pathogens can
move among the world's population centers." In that same document,
Appendix C the term outbreak and epidemic are used interchangeably and are
defined as "multiple confirmed cases in humans".
In Grein TW, Kamara KBO, Rodier G, Plant AJ, Bovier P, Ryan MJ, Ohyama T
and Heymann DL Rumors of Disease in the Global Village: Outbreak
Verification EID 6:2 Mar-Apr 2000, there is a good definition of outbreak
as used by the World Health Organization. "Upon receipt of feedback, the
outbreak verification team determines if the event meets the definition of
an outbreak (observed number of cases exceeds expected number of cases in a
given population for a given period) and the criteria for international
public health importance. Reaching a final decision may require further
consultation with the WHO regional office or the country representative or
health authorities in-country."
Given these two definitions, it seems that the marked increases in reported
cases and deaths due to West Nile virus infection in Israel over the past
two months would meet both the CDC and the WHO working definitions of
"outbreak/epidemic". - Mod.MPP
